indicators.title: PDO 1 Number of technologies that are being made available to farmers and other end users
indicators.description:
Technology refers to the tools, methods or machinery that are used to support agricultural enterprise. There are many categories of agricultural technologies within the production to marketing value chain, and these include mechanical, biological, chemical, and agronomic innovations.  For APPSA new varieties denote those released in the past 5 years since the commencement of the program, i.e. from 2008 onwards.

Availability will be measured by whether seed or agronomic and postharvest practices are being produced and distributed, or a technology has been or is being promoted by the public or private sector. Technologies will be disaggregated by commodity and according to whether they address a cross cutting priority – such as climate change adaptation, gender, nutrition.
“Farmer”: an individual involved in crop and animal production for food, income or raw materials.
“End User”: Consumers/companies that utilize crop and animal produce.

indicators.title: PDO 4 Number of direct project beneficiaries ('000)
indicators.description:
Direct beneficiaries refers to the persons (e.g. Lead Farmers, contact farmers, other farmers and their dependent family members living in the same household) in the project target region who in the first instance utilize project outputs (i.e., knowledge, and technologies) AND their immediate household members.

Household members are included in the beneficiary count of dissemination projects as the project is intended to bring changes in their livelihood too.

indicators.title: Number of lead farmers trained
indicators.description:
Lead farmers trained in APPSA promoted technologies by the RCoL.
“Lead farmers” represent the group of innovative and successful farmers within the local community who are committed to training their fellow farmers on agriculture methods and technologies. Typically, they are selected by the community and registered as lead farmers with the field extension office in a given administrative unit (e.g. district, EPA, block, camp). They are in direct contact with researcher or extension personnel to help champion the demonstration of a technology in their areas.

indicators.title: Number of IEC materials published
indicators.description: Information Education Communication (IEC) materials include brochures, success stories, pamphlets, briefs, extension manuals, flyers, posters, fact sheets and bulletins. The indicator describes IEC materials developed and published by RCoL.

indicators.title: Number of IEC materials distributed
indicators.description: IEC materials include brochures, success stories, pamphlets, briefs, extension manuals, flyers, posters, fact sheets and bulletins printed and distributed by RCoL. The indicator describes Information Education Communication (IEC) materials printed and distributed or shared electronically by RCoL to stakeholders.

indicators.title: Number of sms messages dispatched to lead farmers on promoted technologies
indicators.description: Number of messages (content) dispatched to lead farmers on promoted technologies by the RCoL. The messages can be in different languages.

indicators.title: Number of sms responses by lead farmers
indicators.description: Total number/percentage of responses by lead farmers made to the RCoL.

indicators.title: Number of TV documentaries produced and aired
indicators.description: TV documentaries sponsored by APPSA to reach the target population with a message on a specific technology or practice.

indicators.title: Number of radio programs produced and aired
indicators.description: Radio programs sponsored by APPSA to reach the target population with a message on a specific technology.

indicators.title: Quantity of breeder seed produced
indicators.description: Breeder Seed is produced under direct supervision of the plant breeder and represents the true pedigree of the variety. Normally available in small quantities (Kgs), and is planted to produce foundation/basic seed.

indicators.title: Quantity of foundation/basic seed produced
indicators.description: Foundation/basic Seed is the first generation of seed multiplication using the breeder seed. It is produced under direct control of a seed quality and certification unit or a similar formal entity. It is available in limited quantities, (Kgs) and is planted to produce certified seed.

indicators.title: Quantity of certified seeds produced
indicators.description: Certified Seed is produced from foundation/basic seed. It is available in large quantities (tons), and is sold to farmers for general grain production. Typically it is produced by seed companies, directly or under contract farming.

indicators.title: Number of improved varieties released by the RCoL that can be accessed by farmers
indicators.description:
Certified crop seed varieties that are registered under ZARI/IIAM/DARS and were either generated or disseminated with the help of APPSA research funds.  An improved variety is deemed accessible to farmers if it is available to 40% of the marketing outlets in the target districts
Note: “Accessed by farmers“ means that it can be acquired or purchased on the local market (e.g. stocked with agro dealers, government subsidized inputs)

indicators.title: Number of technologies released by a RCoL in two countries and that can be  accessed by Farmers
indicators.description:
Certified seed varieties, agronomic and postharvest practices that are registered in two APPSA program countries under the name of one of the three institutions ZARI/IIAM/DARS, and which were either generated or disseminated with the help of APPSA research funds.
Note: “accessed by farmers” means that it can be acquired or purchased on the local market (e.g. stocked with agro dealers, government subsided inputs).

indicators.title: Number of improved technologies (varieties/management practices) being promoted to farmers through the existing innovation platforms
indicators.description: An innovation platform is a space for learning and change. It is a group of individuals (who often represent organizations) with different backgrounds and interests including farmers, traders, food processors, researchers, government officials, etc.

indicators.title: Proportion of participatory research projects in RCoL portfolio
indicators.description: Participatory research comprises a range of methodological approaches and techniques, all with the objective of handing power from the researcher to research participants, who are often community members or community-based organizations. In participatory research, participants have control over the research agenda, the process and actions. Most importantly, people themselves are the ones who analyze and reflect on the information generated, in order to obtain the findings and conclusions of the research process.

indicators.title: Number of R&D consultative meetings with stakeholders
indicators.description: A consultative meeting is a forum where stakeholders meet to take stock of achievements, review R&D priorities and plan for the way forward. A broader group of stakeholders includes investors, policy makers, farmers/farmer representative, seed companies, processors, CSOs, NGOs, CGIAR centers, universities etc.

indicators.title: Number of National Steering Committee meetings held
indicators.description: A steering committee is a committee that decides on the priorities or order of business in compliance with its formally agreed Terms of Reference.
